# Mann
1. Societies are constituted of multiple overlapping and intersecting sociospatial networks of power.
2. Societies, their structure & history can best be analyzed in terms of interrelations of four sources of social power: IEMP relationships.
Systemic/unitary conception: a society is a network of social interaction at the boundaries of which is a certain level of interaction cleavage betweent it and its environment.
societies are not
- unitary
- totalities
- systems (is Mann still a system theorist?)
central problems concern: organization, control, logistics, communication: "capacity to organize and control people, materials and territories" (= legitimacy nach Weber?)
- four sources have different means of social control
- legitimacy as measure of the effectiveness or stability of a political network?
	- political power in turkey leans on ideological network, so being related to it stabilizes the turkish political system
no ultimate primacy
- intuitionists are wrong and working on implicit assumptions - commonsense stops working when its not universal anymore
human nature
- restless, purposive, rational, happiness, capable of choosing means to do so.
- not all, but enough ppl do this to form a distinctive human history
- this dynamism is original source of power
- human goals require 1. intervention in nature, and 2. social cooperation
- human beings pursuing their goals is not further questioned
power
- ability to pursue & attain goals through mastery of one's environment
- social power: distributive and collective power
	- distributive power: A's will > B`s will
	- collective power: A+B's will > C`s will
- range of power:
	- extensive power: large number of ppl, far territory
	- intensive power: tight organization, high level of mobilization
	- authoritative power: definite commands and conscious obedience
	- diffused power: spontaneous, unconscious, decentered actions in the same direction
networks:
- ideological/status
- economical/class
- political: centralized, institutionalized, territorial regulation
- military: organized physical force
interstitial emergence
- creation of new societies in the pores of the old ones
ideological power (status): transcendent or immanent
- meaning
- norms
- ritual practices
economic power: circuits of praxis
- modes of production (marxist focus)
- organization of exchange (weberian focus)
- economic organization comprises circuits of production, distribution, exchange and consumption
military power:
- concentrated-coercive
- extensive, frightening reach
- sociospatially dual: 
	- concentrated core for positive, coerced control
	- extensive area in which certain compliance will not be overstepped, but behaviour cant be positively controlled
political power:
- regulations and coercion centrally administered and territorally bounded (state power)
- located in a center and exercized outward
- sociospatially dual: domestic vs international organization
- territorally centralized; can attain greater power when social life generates possibilities for enhanced cooperation & exploitation in a confined territoral area
- geopolitical diplomacy. two types:
	- hegemonic empire dominating neighbours
	- multistate civilization

