# Gerschewski
Stability of all autocracies can be explained with 3 Pillars of stability:
- legitimation
- repression
- co-optation
Sources of regime breakdown:
- civil uprising
- organized opposition
- splits in the elite
Legitimation
- empirical, weberian legitimacy belief
- diffuse & specific support
- measurement of specific support: economical, social and public order success (GDP, GINI social inequality, HDI, riot/strike/crime rate...)
- measurement of diffuse support is hard to take: either put lots of effort into data, or believe the regimes claims of legitimacy
Repression
- costly and not enough in the long-term, because "you cant sit on bayonettes"
Co-optation
- tying strategically-relevent actors to the regime elite
- inclusionary, participationary... parliaments, patronage, clientelism, corruption provide this stability
- elite rules through network of direct and indirect ties to subordinates
- difficult to measure, complex indicators have been enough for past autocracies
Interaction between these pillars serves all of them
Self-reciprocating dynamics inside the pillars



